  "description": [
    "Between The Lines Eisenhower on General Principles Within a few days the voters of these United States will elect a President to guide the destinies of the nation for another four years It is not too early for the informed voter to make up his mind For a group that is op pressed and depressed and re pressed and oftimes distressed like the Negro there is only one question and that is whose candidacy and administration promises relief In pther words the Negro is fighting for survival in this coun try and the civil rights issue is paramount State rights and civil rights are antipodal issues and shrewd politicians have made them mutually exclusive It was not so from the beginning but it is so now and if these same poli ticians have their way it will be so forevermore During the elec tion in 1952 the issue was clear cut and the South that is the Old South went over srongly for Eisenhower There was evidently hope that Eisenhower would lean heavily toward States rights each one of which is designed to limit the civil rights of Negroes and so the Old South fell hard for Eisen hower Stevenson"
  ],
